8 PROPOSED OVERSIGHT COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
9 An Act relating to medical expenses; defining terms;
authorizing individuals to pay for medical expenses
10 out-of-pocket; directing insurance providers to count
certain payments toward deductibles, coinsurance, and
11 copayments; providing for documentation requirements;
providing for codification; and providing an
12 effective date.
13
14
15 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
16 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
17 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 6060.50 of Title 36, unless
18 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
19 As used in this section:
20 1. "Health care service" means any services provided by a
21 health care provider, or by an individual working for or under the
22 supervision of a health care provider, that relate to the diagnosis,
23 assessment, prevention, treatment, or care of any human illness,
24
Req. No. 13220 Page 1
1 dise ase, injury, or condition, as defined by paragraph 2 of Section
2 1-1708.1C of Title 63 of the Oklahoma Statutes.
3 The term also includes the provision of mental health and
4 substance use disorder services, as defined by Section 6060.10 of
5 Title 36 of the Oklahoma Statutes, and the provision of durable
6 medical equipment. The term does not include the provision,
7 administration, or prescription of pharmaceutical products or
8 services; and
9 2. "Health benefit plan" means group hospital coverage,
10 individual and group medical insurance coverage, a not-for-profit
11 hospital or medical service or indemnity plan, a prepaid health
12 plan, a health maintenance organization plan, a preferred provider
13 organization plan, the State and Education Employees Group Health
14 Insurance Plan, and coverage provided by a Multiple Employer Welfare
15 Arrangement. The term "health benefit plan" shall not include:
16 a. a plan that provides coverage:
17 (1) only for a specified disease or diseases or under
18 an individual limited benefit policy,
19 (2) only for accidental death or dismemberment,
20 (3) only for dental or vision care,
21 (4) a hospital confinement indemnity policy,
22 (5) disability income insurance or a combination of
23 accident-only and disability income insurance, or
24 (6) as a supplement to liability insurance,
Req. No. 13220 Page 2
1 b. any health plan offered by a contracted entity, as
2 defined in Section 4002.2 of Title 56 of the Oklahoma
3 Statutes, that provides coverage to members of the
4 state Medicaid program,
5 c. a Medicare supplemental policy as defined by Section
6 1882(g)(1) of the Social Security Act (42 U.S.C.,
7 Section 1395ss),
8 d. workers' compensation insurance coverage,
9 e. medical payment insurance issued as part of a motor
10 vehicle insurance policy,
11 f. a long-term care policy, including a nursing home
12 fixed indemnity policy, unless a determination is made
13 that the policy provides benefit coverage so
14 comprehensive that the policy meets the definition of
15 a health benefit plan, or
16 g. short-term health insurance issued on a nonrenewable
17 basis with a duration of six (6) months or less.
18 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
19 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 6060.51 of Title 36, unless
20 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
21 A. An enrollee may choose to pay for a health care service out-
22 of-pocket from a licensed health care provider. If an enrollee
23 obtains a medically necessary health care service covered by the
24 enrollee's health benefit plan and negotiates for a lower price from
Req. No. 13220 Page 3
1 a li censed health care provider than the average allowed amount
2 established by the enrollee's health benefits plan for the covered
3 health care service, and the enrollee pays for the health care
4 service out-of-pocket, the enrollee may send documentation, which
5 may be sent electronically, to the carrier, that provides the
6 following:
7 1. The health care service the enrollee or patient received and
8 the licensed health care provider's name and contact information;
9 2. If a health care provider's order is required by the
10 enrollee's policy, the order from the health care provider given to
11 the enrollee or patient and the final bill or statement for the
12 health care service;
13 3. The negotiated cost of the health care service that the
14 enrollee received:
15 a. the enrollee paid out-of-pocket for the health care
16 services received, and
17 b. the health care entity is not making a claim against
18 the carrier for payment for the health care service
19 provided to the enrollee or patient; and
20 4. The health care provider shall accept the enrollee's payment
21 as payment in full and shall not bill the enrollee or the health
22 benefit plan for any balance between the amount collected from the
23 enrollee and the provider's billed charge for the service.
24
Req. No. 13220 Page 4
1 B. A carrier that receives the documentation described in
2 subsection A of this section shall count the full amount that the
3 enrollee paid out-of-pocket toward the enrollee's deductible, and
4 annual maximum out-of-pocket expense:
5 1. If the health care service is covered under the enrollee's
6 health benefit plan; and
7 2. The enrollee negotiated for a lower cost for the health care
8 service than the average allowed amount established by the
9 enrollee's health benefit plan for that covered health care service.
10 C. The amount of the enrollee's out-of-pocket cost shall be
11 attributed to the in-network deductible, and annual maximum out-of-
12 pocket expense, if the provider was an in-network provider, and to
13 the out-of-network deductible, and annual maximum out-of-pocket
14 expense if the provider was an out-of-network provider.
15 D. The amount counted toward an enrollee's applicable out-of-
16 pocket deductible, and annual maximum out-of-pocket expense shall
17 not exceed the total amount that the enrollee is required to pay
18 out-of-pocket during a contractually agreed upon period of time for
19 health care services that are included under the covered person's
20 insurance plan, and does not carry over once a new contract or
21 agreement period for the insurance plan begins.
22 SECTION 3. This act shall become effective November 1, 2025.
